go,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Llwyn-Dafydd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1334–":"circa 1334–Overleden","1334–Female":"1334–Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1358–Female":"1358–Overleden","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","1362–Female":"1362–Overleden","1368–Male":"1368–Overleden","1370–Male":"1370–Overleden","1380–Female":"1380–Overleden","–1501":"–1501","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1308–Male":"1308–Overleden","1312–Female":"1312–Overleden","ABT    1368":"circa 1368","ABT    1362":"circa 1362","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","ABT    1358":"circa 1358","1501":"1501","1358":"1358","1368":"1368","1312":"1312","1334":"1334","about 1334":"circa 1334","ABT    1380":"circa 1380","1308":"1308","of,,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Llwyn Dafydd,Llandysiliogogo,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Llwyn-Dafydd, Cardiganshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1334–":"about 1334–Deceased","1334–Female":"1334–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1358–Female":"1358–Deceased","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1362–Female":"1362–Deceased","1368–Male":"1368–Deceased","1370–Male":"1370–Deceased","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","–1501":"–1501","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1308–Male":"1308–Deceased","1312–Female":"1312–Deceased","ABT    1368":"about 1368","ABT    1362":"about 1362","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","ABT    1358":"about 1358","1501":"1501","1358":"1358","1368":"1368","1312":"1312","1334":"1334","about 1334":"about 1334","ABT    1380":"about 1380","1308":"1308","of,,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Llwyn Dafydd,Llandysiliogogo,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Llwyn-Dafydd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Philip","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Varughese, Mathai, Babu, Reji, Anil, Binu, Neena, Prema, Raju, Reena, Susheela, Aleykutty.","Scottish, English, German, Dutch, and Jewish: from the Greek personal name <i>Philippos</i> (from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’). In the New Testament this name is borne by one of the apostles; it was also borne by various other early Christian saints. It owes part of its popularity to the medieval romances about Alexander the Great, whose father was Philip of Macedon. As a Jewish name, it represents a borrowing of the personal name from Christians. As a Highland Scottish surname, it represents an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‘son of Philip’. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Spanish   Felipe  , Catalan <b>Felip</b>, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian or Croatian   Filip  , Albanian   Filipi  , and their derivatives (see examples at   Philips  ). The name <i>Philip</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Philipose   and   Pothen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Phillip  .","French (southern) and Breton (Finistère): variant of   Philippe  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McKillip","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‘son of Philip’ (see   Philip  ). See also   McPhillips  ."]},{"name":"Felipe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Juana, Miguel, Orlando, Pedro, Angel, Carlos, Emilio, Jesus.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Felipe</i>, an equivalent of   Philippe  ."]},{"name":"Lips","meanings":["North German, Flemish, and Dutch: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Philips</i>, from Latin <i>Philippus</i> (see   Philip  )."]},{"name":"Lipps","meanings":["North German: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Philipps</i>, from Latin <i>Philippus</i> (see   Philip  )."]},{"name":"Pepin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Camille, Emile, Pierre, Gilles, Lucien, Normand, Alcide, Fernand, Jacques, Marcel.","French (<b>Pépin</b>) and English: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Pipin</i>, of uncertain, probably onomatopoeic origin. The name was borne by several Frankish kings, most notably Pepin le Bref, father of Charlemagne, and remained popular throughout the early Middle Ages.","English: from the unrecorded Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal names <i>Pipin</i>, <i>Pepin</i>, <i>Pipun</i>, pet forms of   Philip  . Compare   Pipe  ."]},{"name":"Lippens","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alfons, Alphons.  French Andre.","Flemish and Dutch: patronymic from a shortened form of the personal name   Philip  ."]},{"name":"Philbin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Philbín</b>, ‘son of Philbin (Irish <i>Philbín</i> or <i>Filibín</i>)’, a pet form of   Philip  ."]},{"name":"Lipman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Mayer, Chaim, Dov, Isadore, Jakob, Meyer, Pinchas.","Dutch: habitational name from a farm named Lipman or perhaps Lippink, referring to a certain <i>Lippo</i> and his kin. <i>Lippo</i> is a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name composed with the element <i>leiba</i> ‘offspring, son’, or of the personal name   Philip  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish personal name <i>Lipman</i>, derived from Middle High German words <i>liep</i> ‘dear, beloved’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Philipose","meanings":["Indian (Kerala): from the personal name <i>Philipose</i>, derived from Greek <i>Philippos</i> (see   Philip  ), found among Christians in southern India. — Note: Since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, this name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Philibert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Fernand, Mirielle, Pascale, Pierrot.","French: from the personal name <i>Philibert</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Filuberht</i>, composed of the elements <i>fila</i> ‘much, very’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright’, which was borne by a 7th-century Christian saint, abbot of Jumièges. The spelling has been influenced by personal names of Greek origin based on <i>philein</i> ‘to love’, e.g.   Philip  ."]}]},{"name":"Lleucu","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Lucia</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old English <i>fearn</i>). Modern use of this word as a given name dates from the 19th century, when it is also recorded occasionally as a boy's name in the United States. In some instances the given name may be a transferred use of the surname derived in the medieval period from the vocabulary word."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lleucu ferch Philip was born about 1334, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Philip ap Llywelyn, was 28 and her mother, Mrs. Philip ap Llywelyn, was 24. She had at least 5 sons and 5 daughters with Dafydd Ieuan."},"et":{"about 1334–":"umbes 1334–Surnud","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1358–Female":"1358–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1362–Female":"1362–Surnud","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","–1501":"–1501","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnu